  "response_text": "# Realistic Marathon Training for Your Situation\n\n## Honest Assessment First\nTraining for a marathon on two jobs is ambitious. Consider:\n- A half-marathon might be more sustainable while you're working this much\n- 16-20 weeks of training requires 4-5 days/week running\n- Sleep and recovery matter—exhaustion increases injury risk\n\n## Budget-Conscious Shoe Strategy\n**One pair under $30 for a year:**\n- Look for sales at outlet stores, clearance racks, or previous-season models\n- Brands like New Balance, ASICS occasionally have $20-25 options\n- Make it last: rotate with walking shoes to extend life, hand wash when possible\n- Accept you'll likely need a second pair mid-year—budget for it or adjust goals\n\n## Realistic 12-Week Schedule (if committed)\n**Days 1-2, 4-5: Easy runs** (20-30 min)\n**Day 3: Rest or walk**\n**Day 6: Long run** (gradually 5→12 miles)\n**Day 7: Rest**\n\nRun at conversational pace. Skip speed work—it demands more recovery.\n\n## Real Talk\n- Working two jobs + marathon training = high burnout/injury risk\n- Your body needs sleep more than it needs race medals\n- A local 5K or 10K might give you the finish-line experience with less sacrifice\n\nWhat's driving the marathon goal? There might be a version that fits your life better.",
